# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anthropology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Abductive reasoning, unlike deductive reasoning, yields a plausible conclusion but does not definitively verify it.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Abductive conclusions do not eliminate uncertainty or doubt, which is expressed in terms such as "best available" or "most likely".
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] While inductive reasoning draws general conclusions that apply to many situations, abductive conclusions are confined to the particular observations in question.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In the 1990s, as computing power grew, the fields of law, computer science, and artificial intelligence research spurred renewed interest in the subject of abduction.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Diagnostic expert systems frequently employ abduction.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning allows deriving b from a only where b is a formal logical consequence of a .
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In other words, deduction derives the consequences of the assumed.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Given the truth of the assumptions, a valid deduction guarantees the truth of the conclusion.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] For example, given that "Socrates is a man" ( $a_{1}$ ) and "All men are mortal" ( $a_{2}$ ), it follows that "Socrates is mortal" ( b ).
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Inductive reasoning is the process of inferring some *general* principle b from a body of knowledge a , where b does not necessarily follow from a . a might give us very good reason to accept b but does not ensure b .
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] For example, if all swans that a person has observed so far are white, they may infer a universal categorical proposition of the form *All swans are white*.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] They have good reason to believe the conclusion from the premise because it is the *best explanation* for their observations, but the truth of the conclusion is not guaranteed.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Indeed, it turns out that some swans are black.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Abductive reasoning allows inferring a as an explanation of b .
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] As a result of this inference, abduction allows the precondition a to be abducted from the consequence b .
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning and abductive reasoning differ in which end, left or right, of the proposition " a entails b " serves as the conclusion.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] For example, with deductive reasoning, knowing that it rained heavily during the night, you could deduce that the lawn will be wet in the morning without looking outside.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] With abductive reasoning, a couple leaving their house in the morning and seeing that their lawn is wet might abduce that it rained while they were asleep.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] This serves as a hypothesis that "best explains" their observation.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Given the many possible explanations for the lawn getting wet, their abduction does not establish certainty that it rained overnight, but it is still useful and can serve to orient them in their surroundings.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Despite many possible explanations for any physical process we observe, we tend to abduce a single explanation (or a few) for this process in the expectation that we can better orient ourselves in our surroundings and disregard some possibilities.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Properly used, abductive reasoning can be a useful source of priors in Bayesian statistics.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] One can understand abductive reasoning as inference to the best explanation, although the terms *abduction* and *inference to the best explanation* are not always used equivalently.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In logic, explanation is accomplished through the use of a logical theory T representing a domain and a set of observations O .
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is the process of deriving a set of explanations of O according to T and picking out one of those explanations.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In formal logic, O and E are assumed to be sets of literals.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Among the possible explanations E satisfying these two conditions, some other condition of minimality is usually imposed to avoid irrelevant facts (not contributing to the entailment of O ) being included in the explanations.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is then the process that picks out some member of E .
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Criteria for picking out a member representing "the best" explanation include the simplicity, the prior probability, or the explanatory power of the explanation.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] A proof-theoretical abduction method for first-order classical logic based on the sequent calculus and a dual one, based on semantic tableaux (analytic tableaux) have been proposed.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The methods are sound and complete and work for full first-order logic, without requiring any preliminary reduction of formulae into normal forms.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] These methods have also been extended to modal logic.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Abductive logic programming is a computational framework that extends normal logic programming with abduction.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] It separates the theory T into two components, one of which is a normal logic program, used to generate E by means of backward reasoning, the other of which is a set of integrity constraints, used to filter the set of candidate explanations.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] A different formalization of abduction is based on inverting the function that calculates the visible effects of the hypotheses.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Formally, we are given a set of hypotheses H and a set of manifestations M ; they are related by the domain knowledge, represented by a function e that takes as an argument a set of hypotheses and gives as a result the corresponding set of manifestations.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In other words, for every subset of the hypotheses $H'\subseteq H$ , their effects are known to be $e(H')$ .
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is performed by finding a set $H'\subseteq H$ such that $M\subseteq e(H')$ .
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In other words, abduction is performed by finding a set of hypotheses $H'$ such that their effects $e(H')$ include all observations M .
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] A common assumption is that the effects of the hypotheses are independent, that is, for every $H'\subseteq H$ , it holds that $e(H')=\bigcup _{h\in H'}e(\{h\})$ .
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] If this condition is met, abduction can be seen as a form of set covering.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Abductive validation is the process of validating a given hypothesis through abductive reasoning.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] This can also be called reasoning through successive approximation.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Under this principle, an explanation is valid if it is the best possible explanation of a set of known data.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The best possible explanation is often defined in terms of simplicity and elegance (see Occam's razor).
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Subjective logic generalises probabilistic logic by including degrees of epistemic uncertainty in the input arguments, i.e. instead of probabilities, the analyst can express arguments as subjective opinions.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction in subjective logic is thus a generalization of probabilistic abduction described above.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The input arguments in subjective logic are subjective opinions which can be binomial when the opinion applies to a binary variable or multinomial when it applies to an *n*-ary variable.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Assume the domains $\mathbf {X}$ and $\mathbf {Y}$ with respective variables X and Y , the set of conditional opinions $\omega _{X\mid Y}$ (i.e. one conditional opinion for each value y ), and the base rate distribution $a_{Y}$ .
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Using these inverted conditionals together with the opinion $\omega _{X}$ subjective deduction denoted by the operator $\circledcirc$ can be used to abduce the marginal opinion $\omega _{Y\,{\overline {\|}}\,X}$ .
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The symbolic notation for subjective abduction is " ${\widetilde {\|}}$ ", and the operator itself is denoted as " ${\widetilde {\circledcirc }}$ ".
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The operator for the subjective Bayes' theorem is denoted " ${\widetilde {\phi \,}}$ ", and subjective deduction is denoted " $\circledcirc$ ".
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The advantage of using subjective logic abduction compared to probabilistic abduction is that both aleatoric and epistemic uncertainty about the input argument probabilities can be explicitly expressed and taken into account during the analysis.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] It is thus possible to perform abductive analysis in the presence of uncertain arguments, which naturally results in degrees of uncertainty in the output conclusions.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The idea that the simplest, most easily verifiable solution should be preferred over its more complicated counterparts is a very old one.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] To this point, George Pólya, in his treatise on problem-solving, makes reference to the following Latin truism: *simplex sigillum veri* (simplicity is the seal of truth).
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The American philosopher Charles Sanders Peirce introduced abduction into modern logic.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Over the years he called such inference *hypothesis*, *abduction*, *presumption*, and *retroduction*.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] He considered it a topic in logic as a normative field in philosophy, not in purely formal or mathematical logic, and eventually as a topic also in economics of research.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] As two stages of the development, extension, etc., of a hypothesis in scientific inquiry, abduction and also induction are often collapsed into one overarching concept—the hypothesis.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] That is why, in the scientific method known from Galileo and Bacon, the abductive stage of hypothesis formation is conceptualized simply as induction.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Thus, in the twentieth century this collapse was reinforced by Karl Popper's explication of the hypothetico-deductive model, where the hypothesis is considered to be just "a guess" (in the spirit of Peirce).
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] However, when the formation of a hypothesis is considered the result of a process it becomes clear that this "guess" has already been tried and made more robust in thought as a necessary stage of its acquiring the status of hypothesis.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Indeed, many abductions are rejected or heavily modified by subsequent abductions before they ever reach this stage.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Before 1900, Peirce treated abduction as the use of a known rule to explain an observation.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] For instance: it is a known rule that, if it rains, grass gets wet; so, to explain the fact that the grass on this lawn is wet, one *abduces* that it has rained.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction can lead to false conclusions if other rules that might explain the observation are not taken into account—e.g. the grass could be wet from dew.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] This remains the common use of the term "abduction" in the social sciences and in artificial intelligence.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Peirce consistently characterized it as the kind of inference that originates a hypothesis by concluding in an explanation, though an unassured one, for some very curious or surprising (anomalous) observation stated in a premise.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] As early as 1865 he wrote that all conceptions of cause and force are reached through hypothetical inference; in the 1900s he wrote that all explanatory content of theories is reached through abduction.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In other respects Peirce revised his view of abduction over the years.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In Peirce's *On the Natural Classification of Arguments* (1867), hypothetical inference always deals with a cluster of characters (call them *P′, P′′, P′′′,* etc.) known to occur at least whenever a certain character (*M*) occurs.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Note that categorical syllogisms have elements traditionally called middles, predicates, and subjects.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] For example: All *men* [middle] are *mortal* [predicate]; *Socrates* [subject] is a *man* [middle]; ergo *Socrates* [subject] is *mortal* [predicate]".
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Below, 'M' stands for a middle; 'P' for a predicate; 'S' for a subject.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Peirce held that all deduction can be put into the form of the categorical syllogism Barbara (AAA-1).
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In 1878, in *Deduction, Induction, and Hypothesis*, there is no longer a need for multiple characters or predicates in order for an inference to be hypothetical, although it is still helpful.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Moreover, Peirce no longer poses hypothetical inference as concluding in a *probable* hypothesis.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In the forms themselves, it is understood but not explicit that induction involves random selection and that hypothetical inference involves response to a "very curious circumstance".
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The forms instead emphasize the modes of inference as rearrangements of one another's propositions (without the bracketed hints shown below).
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Peirce long treated abduction in terms of induction from characters or traits (weighed, not counted like objects), explicitly so in his influential 1883 "A theory of probable inference", in which he returns to involving probability in the hypothetical conclusion.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Like *Deduction, Induction, and Hypothesis* in 1878, it was widely read (see the historical books on statistics by Stephen Stigler), unlike his later amendments of his conception of abduction.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Today abduction remains most commonly understood as induction from characters and extension of a known rule to cover unexplained circumstances.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Sherlock Holmes used this method of reasoning in the stories of Arthur Conan Doyle, although Holmes refers to it as "deductive reasoning".
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In 1902 Peirce wrote that he now regarded the syllogistical forms and the doctrine of extension and comprehension (i.e., objects and characters as referenced by terms), as being less fundamental than he had earlier thought.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The hypothesis is framed, but not asserted, in a premise, then asserted as rationally suspectable in the conclusion.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Thus, as in the earlier categorical syllogistic form, the conclusion is formulated from some premise(s).
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] But all the same the hypothesis consists more clearly than ever in a new or outside idea beyond what is known or observed.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Induction in a sense goes beyond observations already reported in the premises, but it merely amplifies ideas already known to represent occurrences, or tests an idea supplied by hypothesis; either way it requires previous abductions in order to get such ideas in the first place.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Induction seeks facts to test a hypothesis; abduction seeks a hypothesis to account for facts.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Note that the hypothesis ("A") could be of a rule.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] It need not even be a rule strictly necessitating the surprising observation ("C"), which needs to follow only as a "matter of course"; or the "course" itself could amount to some known rule, merely alluded to, and also not necessarily a rule of strict necessity.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Peirce did not remain quite convinced about any such form as the categorical syllogistic form or the 1903 form.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In 1911, he wrote, "I do not, at present, feel quite convinced that any logical form can be assigned that will cover all 'Retroductions'.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] It is a method for fruitful clarification of conceptions by equating the meaning of a conception with the conceivable practical implications of its object's conceived effects.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Peirce held that that is precisely tailored to abduction's purpose in inquiry, the forming of an idea that could conceivably shape informed conduct.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In various writings in the 1900s he said that the conduct of abduction (or retroduction) is governed by considerations of economy, belonging in particular to the economics of research.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] He regarded economics as a normative science whose analytic portion might be part of logical methodeutic (that is, theory of inquiry).
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Logical critic, or logic proper, on validity or justifiability of inference, the conditions for true representation.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Critique of arguments in their various modes (deduction, induction, abduction).
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Methodeutic, or speculative rhetoric, on the conditions for determination of interpretations.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Methodology of inquiry in its interplay of modes.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Peirce had, from the start, seen the modes of inference as being coordinated together in scientific inquiry and, by the 1900s, held that hypothetical inference in particular is inadequately treated at the level of critique of arguments.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] To increase the assurance of a hypothetical conclusion, one needs to deduce implications about evidence to be found, predictions which induction can test through observation so as to evaluate the hypothesis.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] That is Peirce's outline of the scientific method of inquiry, as covered in his inquiry methodology, which includes pragmatism or, as he later called it, pragmaticism, the clarification of ideas in terms of their conceivable implications regarding informed practice.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Induction is inference through an *index* (a sign by factual connection); a sample is an index of the totality from which it is drawn.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Deduction is inference through a *symbol* (a sign by interpretive habit irrespective of resemblance or connection to its object).
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] At the critical level Peirce examined the forms of abductive arguments (as discussed above), and came to hold that the hypothesis should economize explanation for plausibility in terms of the feasible and natural.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In 1908 Peirce described this plausibility in some detail.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The phrase "inference to the best explanation" (not used by Peirce but often applied to hypothetical inference) is not always understood as referring to the most simple and natural hypotheses (such as those with the fewest assumptions).
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] However, in other senses of "best", such as "standing up best to tests", it is hard to know which is the best explanation to form, since one has not tested it yet.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Still, for Peirce, any justification of an abductive inference as "good" is not completed upon its formation as an argument (unlike with induction and deduction) and instead depends also on its methodological role and promise (such as its testability) in advancing inquiry.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Here, considerations such as probability, absent from the treatment of abduction at the critical level, come into play.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Peirce indicated that abductive reasoning is driven by the need for "economy in research"—the expected fact-based productivity of hypotheses, prior to deductive and inductive processes of verification.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] A key concept proposed by him in this regard is "uberty"—the expected fertility and pragmatic value of reasoning.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] This concept seems to be gaining support via association to the Free Energy Principle.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Gilbert Harman was a professor of philosophy at Princeton University.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Harman's 1965 account of the role of "inference to the best explanation" – inferring the existence of that which we need for the best explanation of observable phenomena – has been very influential.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Stephen Jay Gould, in answering the Omphalos hypothesis, claimed that only hypotheses that can be proved incorrect lie within the domain of science and only these hypotheses are good explanations of facts worth inferring to.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Applications in artificial intelligence include fault diagnosis, belief revision, and automated planning.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The most direct application of abduction is that of automatically detecting faults in systems: given a theory relating faults with their effects and a set of observed effects, abduction can be used to derive sets of faults that are likely to be the cause of the problem.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In medicine, abduction can be seen as a component of clinical evaluation and judgment.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The Internist-I diagnostic system, the first AI system that covered the field of Internal Medicine, used abductive reasoning to converge on the most likely causes of a set of patient symptoms that it acquired through an interactive dialog with an expert user.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction can also be used to model automated planning.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Given a logical theory relating action occurrences with their effects (for example, a formula of the event calculus), the problem of finding a plan for reaching a state can be modeled as the problem of abducting a set of literals implying that the final state is the goal state.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In intelligence analysis, analysis of competing hypotheses and Bayesian networks, probabilistic abductive reasoning is used extensively.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Similarly in medical diagnosis and legal reasoning, the same methods are being used, although there have been many examples of errors, especially caused by the base rate fallacy and the prosecutor's fallacy.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Belief revision, the process of adapting beliefs in view of new information, is another field in which abduction has been applied.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The main problem of belief revision is that the new information may be inconsistent with the prior web of beliefs, while the result of the incorporation cannot be inconsistent.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The process of updating the web of beliefs can be done by the use of abduction: once an explanation for the observation has been found, integrating it does not generate inconsistency.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In 1992 Peter Gärdenfors presented a paper which contained a brief survey of the area of belief revision and its relation to updating of logical databases, and explores the relationship between belief revision and nonmonotonic logic.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] This use of abduction is not straightforward, as adding propositional formulae to other propositional formulae can only make inconsistencies worse.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Instead, abduction is done at the level of the ordering of preference of the possible worlds.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Preference models use fuzzy logic or utility models.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In the philosophy of science, abduction has been the key inference method to support scientific realism, and much of the debate about scientific realism is focused on whether abduction is an acceptable method of inference.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In historical linguistics, abduction during language acquisition is often taken to be an essential part of processes of language change such as reanalysis and analogy.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In applied linguistics research, abductive reasoning is starting to be used as an alternative explanation to inductive reasoning, in recognition of anticipated outcomes of qualitative inquiry playing a role in shaping the direction of analysis.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] It is defined as "The use of an unclear premise based on observations, pursuing theories to try to explain it" (Rose et al., 2020, p.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is used as the mechanism for getting from art to agency.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] That is, abduction can explain how works of art inspire a *sensus communis:* the commonly held views shared by members that characterize a given society.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is the answer to this conundrum because the tentative nature of the abduction concept (Peirce likened it to guessing) means that not only can it operate outside of any pre-existing framework, but moreover, it can actually intimate the existence of a framework.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] As Gell reasons in his analysis, the physical existence of the artwork prompts the viewer to perform an abduction that imbues the artwork with intentionality.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] A statue of a goddess, for example, in some senses actually becomes the goddess in the mind of the beholder; and represents not only the form of the deity but also her intentions (which are adduced from the feeling of her very presence).
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Therefore, through abduction, Gell claims that art can have the kind of agency that plants the seeds that grow into cultural myths.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] The power of agency is the power to motivate actions and inspire ultimately the shared understanding that characterizes any given society.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In formal methods, logic is used to specify and prove properties of computer programs.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] Abduction has been used in mechanized reasoning tools to increase the level of automation of the proof activity.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] It led to a program-proof startup company, which was acquired by Facebook, and the Infer program analysis tool, which led to thousands of bugs being prevented in industrial codebases.
[src:anthropology/abductive-reasoning] In addition to inference of function preconditions, abduction has been used to automate inference of invariants for program loops, inference of specifications of unknown code, and in synthesis of the programs themselves.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:anthropology/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The science of abnormal psychology studies two types of behaviors: adaptive and maladaptive behaviors.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Maladaptive behaviors suggest that some problem(s) exist and can also imply that the individual is vulnerable and unable to cope with environmental stress, leading to difficulties functioning in daily life across emotions, thinking, physical actions, and speech.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Adaptive behaviors are well-suited to the nature of people, their lifestyles and surroundings, and the people they communicate with, allowing them to understand each other.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Clinical psychology is the applied field of psychology that seeks to assess, understand, and treat psychological conditions in clinical practice.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The theoretical field known as *abnormal psychology* may form a backdrop to such work.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Still, clinical psychologists in the field are unlikely to use the term 'abnormal' in reference to their practice.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Psychopathology is a similar term to abnormal psychology, but may have more of an implication of an underlying pathology (disease process), which assumes the medical model of mental disturbance and as such, is a term more commonly used in the medical specialty known as psychiatry.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Hippocrates (460–377 BCE) hypothesized that the body and mind become unwell when the so-called humors, vital fluids in the body, become unbalanced.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The four temperaments theory posits four such humors: black bile, yellow bile, phlegm, and blood.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Each humor was associated with a particular temperament: too much phlegm causes a person to be fatigued, too much black bile causes melancholia, yellow bile causes a quick temper, and too much blood causes optimism, cheerfulness, and confidence.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The act of placing individuals with mental illness in a separate facility known as an asylum dates to 1547, when King Henry VIII of England established the St.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] This hospital, nicknamed Bedlam, was famous for its deplorable conditions.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Asylums remained popular throughout the Middle Ages and the Renaissance era.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] These early asylums often had miserable conditions.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Patients were seen as a "burden" to society, locked away and treated almost like beasts to be dealt with, rather than patients needing treatment.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] However, many of the patients received helpful medical treatment.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] There was scientific curiosity into abnormal behavior, although it was rarely investigated in the early asylums.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Inmates in these early asylums were often put on display for profit, as they were viewed as less than human.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The early asylums were basically modifications of the existing criminal institutions.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] In the late 18th century, the idea of humane treatment for patients gained favor due to the work of Philippe Pinel in France.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] He pushed for the idea that the patients should be treated with kindness, and not the cruelty inflicted on them, as if they were animals or criminals.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] His experimental ideas, such as removing the chains from the patients, were met with reluctance.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The experiments in kindness proved a great success, helping reform how mental institutions would be run.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Institutionalization would continue to improve throughout the 19th and 20th centuries, as a result of the work of many humanitarians such as Dorothea Dix and the mental hygiene movement, which promoted the physical well-being of people with mental health conditions.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] "Dix, more than any other figure in the nineteenth century, made people in America and virtually all of Europe aware that the insane were being subjected to incredible abuses." Through this movement, millions of dollars were raised to build new institutions to house the mentally ill.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Mental hospitals grew substantially in number during the 20th century as care for the mentally ill increased.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] By 1939, there were over 400,000 patients in state mental hospitals in the US.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Hospital stays were normally quite long for the patients, with some individuals being treated for many years.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] These hospitals, while better than the asylums of the past, still lacked the means to provide effective treatment for patients.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Even though the reform movement had occurred, patients were often still met with cruel and inhumane treatment.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Things began to change in 1946, when Mary Jane Ward published the influential novel *The Snake Pit*, which was adapted into a popular movie of the same name.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The book called attention to the conditions that people with a mental health condition faced, and helped to spark concern in the general public to create more humane mental health care in these overcrowded hospitals.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] That same year, the National Institute of Mental Health was also created, providing support for training hospital employees and research into patients' conditions.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] During this period, the Hill–Burton Act was also passed, a program that funded mental health hospitals.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Along with the Community Health Services Act of 1963, the Hill–Burton Acts helped create outpatient psychiatric clinics, inpatient general hospitals, and rehabilitation and community consultation centers.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] In the late twentieth century, however, many mental hospitals were closed in many countries.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] In England, for example, only 14 of the 130 psychiatric institutions established in the early 20th century remained open at the start of the 21st century.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Kennedy launched the community health movement in the United States as a "bold new approach" to mental health care, aimed at coordinating mental health services for citizens in mental health centers.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Over the span of 40 years, the United States saw about a 90 percent drop in the number of patients in psychiatric hospitals.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Deinstitutionalisation ended the long-term confinement of patients in isolating mental hospitals, which could and did cause long-term negative adaptations.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] For instance, institutionalizing people with schizophrenia worsens negative symptoms.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] However, the practice is sometimes criticised for a perceived rise in homelessness amongst people who were previously institutionalized, or are presumed to have been in the institution era.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] People have tried to explain and control abnormal behavior for thousands of years.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Historically, there have been three main approaches to abnormal behavior: the supernatural, biological, and psychological traditions.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Abnormal psychology revolves around two major paradigms for explaining mental disorders, the *psychological* paradigm and the *biological* paradigm.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The psychological paradigm focuses more on the humanistic, cognitive, and behavioral causes and effects of psychopathology.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The biological paradigm includes theories that focus more on physical factors, such as genetics and neurochemistry.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] In the first supernatural tradition, also known as the demonological method, abnormal behavior is attributed to agents outside the human body.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] According to this model, abnormal behaviors are caused by demons, aliens, or spirits, or the influences of the Moon, planets, and stars.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] During the Stone Age, trepanning was performed on those who had mental illness, to literally cut the evil spirits out of the victim's head.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Conversely, Ancient Chinese, Ancient Egyptians, and Hebrews believed that these were evil demons or spirits and advocated exorcism.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] By the time of the Greeks and Romans, mental illnesses were thought to be caused by an imbalance of the four humors, which led to treatments such as draining fluids from the brain.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] During the Medieval period, many Europeans believed that the power of witches, demons, and spirits caused abnormal behaviors.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] People with psychological disorders were thought to be possessed by evil spirits that had to be exorcised through religious rituals.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] If exorcism failed, some authorities advocated steps such as confinement, beating, and other types of torture to make the body uninhabitable to witches, demons, and spirits.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The belief that witches, demons, and spirits were responsible for abnormal behavior persisted into the 15th century.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Swiss alchemist, astrologer, and physician Paracelsus (1493–1541), on the other hand, rejected the idea that abnormal behaviors were caused by witches, demons, and spirits and suggested that the movements of the moon and stars influenced people's mind and behaviors.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Some people, especially in developing countries, as well as some followers of religious sects in developed countries, continue to believe that supernatural powers influence human behavior.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] In Western academia, the supernatural tradition has been largely replaced by the biological and psychological traditions.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Throughout history, societies have proposed several explanations for abnormal human behavior.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] In some hunter-gatherer societies, animists have believed that people exhibiting abnormal behavior are possessed by malevolent spirits.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] This idea has been associated with trepanation, the practice of cutting a hole into the individual's skull to release the malevolent spirits.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Although it has been difficult to define abnormal psychology, one definition includes characteristics such as statistical infrequency.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] A more formalized response to spiritual beliefs about abnormality is the practice of exorcism.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Performed by religious authorities, exorcism is thought of as another way to release evil spirits who cause pathological behavior within the person.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] In some instances, individuals exhibiting unusual thoughts or behaviors have been exiled from society, or worse.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Perceived witchcraft, for example, has been punished by death.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Two Catholic Inquisitors wrote the *Malleus Maleficarum* (Latin for "The Hammer Against Witches"), which many Inquisitors and witch-hunters used.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] It contained an early taxonomy of perceived deviant behavior and proposed guidelines for prosecuting deviant individuals.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] In the biological tradition, psychological disorders are attributed to biological causes.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] In the psychological tradition, disorders are attributed to faulty psychological development, and to social context.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The medical or biological perspective holds the belief that most or all abnormal behavior can be attributed to a medical factor; assuming all psychological disorders are diseases.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The Greek physician Hippocrates, considered the father of Western medicine, played a major role in the biological tradition.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Hippocrates and his associates wrote the Hippocratic Corpus between 450 and 350 BC, in which they suggested that abnormal behaviors can be treated like any other disease.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Hippocrates viewed the brain as the seat of consciousness, emotion, intelligence, and wisdom, and believed that disorders involving these functions would logically be located there.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] These ideas of Hippocrates and his associates were later adopted by Galen, the Roman physician.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Galen extended these ideas and developed a strong and influential school of thought within the biological tradition that extended well into the 18th century.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Kendra Cherry, MSEd, states: "The medical approach to abnormal psychology focuses on the biological causes of mental illness.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] This perspective emphasizes understanding the underlying cause of disorders, which might include genetic inheritance, related physical disorders, infections, and chemical imbalances.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] According to Sigmund Freud's structural model, the id, ego, and superego are three theoretical constructs that define the way an individual interacts with the external world, as well as responding to internal forces The Id represents the instinctual drives of an individual that remain unconscious.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The superego represents a person's conscience and their internalization of societal norms and morality.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Finally, the ego serves to realistically integrate the id's drives with the superego's prohibitions.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Lack of development in the superego, or an incoherently developed Superego within an individual, will result in thoughts and actions that are irrational and abnormal, contrary to the norms and beliefs of society.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Unconscious fears drive irrational beliefs and can result in abnormal behavior.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Rational emotive behavior therapy helps to drive irrational and maladaptive beliefs out of one's mind.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The term sociocultural refers to the various circles of influence on the individual, ranging from close friends and family to the institutions and policies of a country or the world as a whole.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Discriminations, whether based on social class, income, race and ethnicity, or gender, can influence the development of abnormal behaviour.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The number of different theoretical perspectives in the field of psychological abnormality has made it difficult to explain psychopathology properly.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The attempt to explain all mental disorders with the same theory leads to reductionism (explaining a disorder or other complex phenomena using only a single idea or perspective).
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Most mental disorders are composed of several factors, which is why one must take into account several theoretical perspectives when attempting to diagnose or explain a particular behavioral abnormality or mental disorder.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Explaining mental disorders with a combination of theoretical perspectives is known as multiple causality.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The diathesis–stress model emphasizes the importance of applying multiple causality to psychopathology, by stressing that both precipitating causes and predisposing causes cause disorders.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] A precipitating cause is an immediate trigger that instigates a person's action or behavior.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] A predisposing cause is an underlying factor that interacts with the immediate factors to result in a disorder.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Both causes play a key role in the development of a psychological disorder.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] For example, high neuroticism antedates most types of psychopathology.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] There is a wide range of mental disorders that are considered to be forms of Abnormal Psychology.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Schizophrenia can be described as a disorder that causes extreme loss of touch with reality.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The Psychotic nature of schizophrenia manifests itself through delusions, as well as auditory and visual hallucinations.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Schizophrenia is known to have a genetic etiology, as well as other biological components, such as brain disruptions in the prenatal development period.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) is characterized by high amounts of inattention and hyperactive impulsiveness.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Inattentive symptoms include not listening, careless errors, disorganization, losing personal belongings, becoming easily distracted, and forgetfulness.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Symptoms of hyperactive impulsiveness include fidgeting, talking excessively, and interrupting others.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Antisocial personality disorder is a cluster of personality traits that lead to specific outcomes and violate others' rights.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] These personality traits include callousness, deceitfulness, lack of remorse, apathy, manipulation of others, impulsiveness, and grandiosity.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Additional traits may include superficial charm, sexual promiscuity, and pathological lying.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Dissociative identity disorder (DID) involves one individual having multiple personalities.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Those with DID are described as having multiple selves that each have their own consciousness and awareness.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] DID has two main etiologies, which are the post-traumatic and socio-cognitive models.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The post-traumatic model states that DID is caused by inescapable past trauma, such as child abuse.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The child dissociates and forms alternate personalities as a coping mechanism in response to the current trauma.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Even when the trauma ends, the personalities continue to disrupt the person's life long-term.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The socio-cognitive model states that people implicitly act as if they have multiple personalities to align with cultural norms.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Those with social anxiety disorder (SAD) have a very intense fear of social situations.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] This fear stems from the belief that the person will be evaluated negatively or embarrass themselves.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] SAD is also considered to be one of the more disabling mental disorders.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Symptoms of this disorder include fear in most, if not all, social situations.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] SAD can develop after a traumatic and/or embarrassing experience has occurred while other people were observing the person.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Generalized anxiety disorder is characterized by a constant, chronic state of worry and anxiety that is related to a large variety of situations and is difficult to control.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Additional symptoms may include irritability, fatigue, concentration difficulties, and restlessness.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Individuals with specific phobias have an extreme fear and avoidance of various objects or situations.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Specifically, fears become phobias when there is excessive and unreasonable fear that is disproportionate to the culture that the individual is in.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Examples of specific phobias include, but are not limited to, phobias of school, blood, injury, needles, small animals, and heights.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) is described as physical and mental distress related to past traumatic experiences.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] PTSD can manifest a large variety of symptoms, including, but not limited to, nightmares, flashbacks, avoidance, and/or physiological reactions related to stimuli regarding the trauma, shame, guilt, anger, hypervigilance, and social withdrawal.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] PTSD symptoms can arise due to various experiences that involve actual or threatened violence, injury, or death.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Firsthand experience, witnessing, or learning about traumatic experiences can lead to the development of PTSD.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The DSM-5 is the manual that contains the most widely discussed and researched information on this topic.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Various conditions have been included in this manual and continue to be added to the DSM-5.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The causes of many of these diseases stem from genetic, biological, sociocultural, systemic, and biopsychosocial factors.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Various counseling theories support and help explain the findings related to each illness.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] In North America, this is the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of the American Psychiatric Association.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The current version of the book is known as the DSM-5.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] It lists a set of disorders and provides detailed descriptions of what constitutes a mental disorder.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The DSM-5 identifies three key elements that must be present to constitute a mental disorder.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The DSM-5 uses three main sections to organize its contents.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Section I includes the introduction, use, and basics of the DSM-5.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Section II includes diagnostic criteria and codes.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Section III includes emerging measures and models.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Section I of the DSM-5 briefly prefaces purpose, content, structure, and use.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] This includes basics, introductions, and cautionary statements for forensic use.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Information is also given about the revision and review processes as well as the DSM-5's goals to harmonize with the ICD-11.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] An explanation regarding the change from the previous multi-axial classification system to the current three-section system is also included here.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Section II of the DSM-5 contains a wide range of diagnostic criteria and codes used to establish and diagnose a vast array of abnormal psychological constructs.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] These categories are used to organize abnormal psychological concepts based on their similarities.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Section III of the DSM-5 contains the various methods and strategies that are used to make clinical decisions, understand culture, and explore emerging diagnoses.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The major international nosologic system for the classification of mental disorders is the International Classification of Diseases, 10th revision (ICD-10).
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The ICD-10 has been used by World Health Organization (WHO) Member States since 1994.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Chapter five covers some 300 mental and behavioral disorders.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The APA's DSM-IV has influenced Chapter 5 of ICD-10, and there is a great deal of concordance between the two.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Beginning in January 2022, the ICD-11 will replace the ICD-10 in WHO member states.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] WHO maintains free access to the ICD-10 Online.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The ICD-11 is the most recent version of the International Classification of Diseases.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The *Mental, behavioral, or Neurodevelopmental disorders section* highlights forms of abnormal psychology.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Psychologists may use different perspectives to gain a better understanding of abnormal psychology.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Some of them may concentrate on a single perspective.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] But professionals prefer to combine two or three perspectives to obtain meaningful information for better treatments.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Psychoanalytic theory is heavily based on the theory of the neurologist Sigmund Freud.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] These ideas often represented repressed emotions and memories from a patient's childhood in the patient's unconscious.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] According to psychoanalytic theory, these repressions cause the disturbances people experience in their daily lives, and by finding their source, one should be able to eliminate them.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] This is accomplished through a variety of methods, including free association, hypnosis, and insight.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The goal of these methods is to induce a catharsis, or emotional release, in the patient, which should indicate that the source of the problem has been tapped and can then be treated.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Freud's psychosexual stages also played a key role in this form of therapy, as he would often believe that the problems the patient was experiencing were due to them becoming stuck, or "fixated", in a particular stage.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Dreams also played a major role in this form of therapy, as Freud viewed dreams as a way to gain insight into the unconscious mind.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Patients were often asked to keep dream journals to bring in for discussion during the next therapy session.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] There are many potential problems associated with this style of therapy, including resistance to the repressed memory or feeling, and negative transference onto the therapist.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Psychoanalysis was carried on by many after Freud, including his daughter Anna Freud, and Jacques Lacan.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Many others have also elaborated on Freud's original theory and added their own take on defense mechanisms or dream analysis.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] While psychoanalysis has fallen out of favor to more modern forms of therapy, it is still used by some clinical psychologists to varying degrees.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Behavior therapy relies on the principles of behaviorism, such as involving classical and operant conditioning.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Behaviorism arose in the early 20th century, from the work of psychologists such as James Watson and B.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Behaviorism states that all behaviors humans do are because of a stimulus and reinforcement.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] While this reinforcement is normally for good behavior, it can also occur for maladaptive behavior.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] In this therapeutic view, the patient's maladaptive behavior has been reinforced, which will lead to its repetition.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The goal of the therapy is to reinforce less maladaptive behaviors so that, over time, these adaptive behaviors become the patient's primary ones.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Humanistic therapy aims to achieve self-actualization (Carl Rogers, 1961).
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] In this style of therapy, the therapist will focus on the patient themselves rather than on the patient's problem.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The goal of this therapy is, by treating the patient as "human", rather than "client", to get to the source of the problem and to resolve the problem effectively.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Humanistic therapy has been on the rise in recent years and is associated with numerous benefits.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] It is considered one of the core elements needed for therapeutic effectiveness and a significant contributor to the well-being of not only the patient but society as a whole.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Some say that all therapeutic approaches today draw on the humanistic approach in some way, and that humanistic therapy is the best way to treat a patient.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Humanistic therapy can be used on people of all ages; it is very popular among children in its variant known as "play therapy".
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Cognitive behavioural therapy (CBT) aims to influence thought and cognition (Beck, 1977).
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] This form of therapy relies on not only the components of behavioral therapy as mentioned before, but also the elements of cognitive psychology.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] This relies on not only the clients behavioral problems that could have arisen from conditioning, but also their negative schemas and distorted perceptions of the world around them.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] These negative schemas may cause distress in the patient's life; for example, they may lead to unrealistic expectations about how well they should perform at work or how they should look.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] When these expectations are not met, it will often result in maladaptive behaviors, such as depression, obsessive compulsions, and anxiety.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] With CBT, the goal is to change the schemas causing stress in the patient's life and replace them with more realistic ones.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Once the negative schemas have been replaced, this will hopefully lead to remission of the patient's symptoms.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] CBT is considered particularly effective in the treatment of depression and has even been used in recent years in group settings.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] It is felt that using CBT in a group setting aids in giving its members a sense of support and decreasing the likelihood of them dropping out of therapy before the treatment has had time to work properly.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] CBT is an effective treatment for many patients, even those who do not have diseases and disorders typically thought of as psychiatric ones.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] For example, patients with the disease multiple sclerosis have found a lot of help using CBT.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The treatment often helps the patients cope with the disorder they have and how they can adapt to their new lives without developing new problems, such as depression or negative schemas about themselves.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] According to RAND, therapies are difficult to provide to all patients in need.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] A lack of funding and understanding of symptoms provides a major roadblock that is not easily avoided.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Individual symptoms and responses to treatment vary, creating a disconnect among patients, society, and caregivers/professionals.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] In play therapy, the clinicians will "play" with their client, usually with toys or a tea party.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Playing is typical child behavior; therefore, playing with the therapist will come naturally to the child.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] While playing together, the clinician will ask the patient questions, and in this setting, they seem less intrusive, more therapeutic, and more like a normal conversation.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] This should help the patient identify their issues and disclose them to the therapist with less difficulty than they may experience in a traditional counseling setting.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Play therapy involves a therapist observing a child as the child plays with toys and interacts with their surrounding environment.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The therapist plays both an observational and an interactional role in the intervention.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] This process allows the child to enact their problems through play and speak more comfortably with the therapist.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Although somewhat controversial, due to data that suggests a lack of effectiveness in children older than 10 years old, play therapy is a valuable treatment.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] This therapy is particularly useful for younger children under 10 who are consciously aware of their environment.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Play therapy is important, given that many therapeutic interventions effective for adults are less effective for children.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Family systems therapies are based on the belief that children's problems stem from issues within the family.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Family systems therapy aims to improve relationships among multiple people within specific families through therapeutic intervention.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] For the best effect, it is recommended that the entire family be included in the therapy.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The treatments include family management skill development and child–parent attachment development.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] These interventions help to improve family functioning.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Family therapists can teach family management skills, including improving supervision and disciplinary practices and creating environments that foster positive interactions between parents and children.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Child–parent attachment development involves altering or creating relationships between parents and children, in attempts to create secure bases for the child, and to facilitate trust, independence, and positive perceptions of family relationships.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] We see these situations a lot more than we think, which makes some spectrums of abnormal psychology more normal and more common.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] These goals are often achieved by creating understanding regarding behaviors, creating opportunities for attachment, and increasing the family's ability to think about their history and relationships.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] One of the primary criticisms of the term "Abnormal Psychology" is its contribution to the stigmatization of individuals with mental health conditions.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] The label "abnormal" implies a deviation from a societal norm, which can reinforce negative stereotypes and social exclusion.
[src:anthropology/abnormal-psychology] Critics argue that such language can lead to individuals feeling marginalized, perpetuating a sense of "otherness" and reinforcing the stigma associated with mental health issues.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] In 1909 it merged with the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society (BFASS) to form the Anti-Slavery and Aborigines' Protection Society (now Anti-Slavery International).
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] The Quaker background and abolitionism were significant in the setting-up of the Society.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] In 1835 Parliamentary MP Thomas Fowell Buxton set up a Parliamentary Select Committee to examine the effect of white settlement on indigenous peoples, and various other colonial issues.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] Though a non-Quaker himself, Buxton was the brother-in-law of Quaker reformer and philanthropist Elizabeth Fry.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] In 1837, British physician Thomas Hodgkin prompted the establishment of The Aborigines Committee at an annual Meeting for Sufferings of Quakers.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] In 1838 some of the findings of Buxton's committee were published as *Information Respecting the Aborigines in the British Colonies*.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] Hodgkin's brother John Hodgkin drafted it, then it was rewritten by Thomas to sharpen the effect and reduce its references to missionary activity.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] Around the same time, The Aborigines' Protection Society (APS) was established, "to ensure the health and well-being and the sovereign, legal and religious rights of the indigenous peoples while also promoting the civilization of the indigenous people who were subjected under colonial powers".
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] Other members brought experience from around the world: Saxe Bannister (Australia), Richard King (North America), John Philip (South Africa).
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] The founders were, on King's account, Buxton, Hodgkin, William Allen, Henry Christy, Thomas Clarkson, and Joseph Sturge.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] Buxton, after the 1833 British abolition of slavery, had taken an interest in particular in the Cape Colony.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] The *Report* of the APS in 1838 put the case that colonisation did not inevitably have detrimental effects on indigenous peoples, as conventional wisdom had it, even to the point of their extinction: if the effects were negative, that was a criticism of the plan and regulation for the colony.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] The Aborigines' Protection Society remained active for about 70 years.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] It operated in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Canada, South Africa and the Congo.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] Its motto was *Ab Uno Sanguine*, meaning "Of One Blood" (from Acts 17:26).
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] Its focus was on equal rights, as Equality before the law, for indigenous people, although it did not extend to the protection and preservation of the cultures of these peoples.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] It aimed to achieve legislation that was not based on race, with "racial amalgamation".
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] There was no commitment therefore to preserving the indigenous peoples as encountered.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] In 1840 the Society reported on the treatment of indigenous peoples of Upper Canada.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] The differing views of Buxton and Hodgkin on how to proceed caused some fundamental divisions in the early years.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] Hodgkin was interested in a forum for both scientific discussion (of early ethnology, a discipline that hardly yet existed separately from the study of language), and protective activities based on lobbying.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] Buxton shortly became caught up in the activist drive that led quickly to the Niger expedition of 1841, the failure of which was a huge personal blow and also drove missionary considerations into the background for a time.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] Hodgkin was unhappy with Buxton's published criticism of Elliott Cresson, and the general British disregard for Liberia as an abolitionist project.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] King issued a prospectus for the new Ethnological Society of London in 1842, following Hodgkin's view that the humanitarian and scientific objectives should from then on be pursued separately.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] In 1842 the purpose of the APS was restated: "to record the history, and promote the advancement, of Uncivilized Tribes".
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] On Buxton's death in 1845, Samuel Gurney took over as President.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] Finances improved, and from 1847 Hodgkin had an assistant as Secretary on the payroll for a period, the activist Louis Alexis Chamerovzow.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] Chamerovzow published on the rights of Māori in 1848, and worked on Charles Dickens as opinion-former, with some success (as Dickens wrote to George Payne Rainsford James).
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] He was a perceptive analyst of the difficulties in reconciling the interests of indigenous people and settlers.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] In 1870 the APS bought Lennox Island (Prince Edward Island) on behalf of a community of the Mi'kmaq people.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] Hodgkin's concerns over the indigenous peoples in the Hudson's Bay Company territory in western Canada were pursued both by correspondence with Sir George Simpson, and in the pages of the *Intelligencer*.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] In 1889 Henry Richard Fox Bourne became its editor, and took over as Chair of the APS.
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] He was a critic of the Emin Pasha Relief Expedition, and used the *Intelligencer* to accuse it for the first time of "atrocities".
[src:anthropology/aborigines-protection-society] The Society continued until 1909, when it merged with the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society to form the Anti-Slavery and Aborigines' Protection Society (now Anti-Slavery International).
[src:anthropology/acculturation] At a group level, acculturation often results in changes to culture, religious practices, health care, and other social institutions.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] There are also significant ramifications on the food, clothing, and language of those becoming introduced to the overarching culture.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] At the individual level, the process of acculturation refers to the socialization process by which foreign-born individuals blend the values, customs, norms, cultural attitudes, and behaviors of the overarching host culture.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] This process has been linked to changes in daily behavior, as well as numerous changes in psychological and physical well-being.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] As enculturation is used to describe the process of first-culture learning, acculturation can be thought of as second-culture learning.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Under natural circumstances which are common in daily life encountered today, acculturation automatically takes a long time spanning several generations.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Physical force can be seen in some instances of acculturation, which can cause it to occur more rapidly, but it is not a main component of the process.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] More commonly, the process occurs through constant pressure and consistent exposure to the more prevalent host culture.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Scholars in different disciplines have developed more than 60 theories of acculturation, though many lack academic rigour in their proposals.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Active academic focus on the concept of acculturation began in 1918.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] As it has been approached from the fields of psychology, anthropology, and sociology at different times, numerous theories and definitions have emerged to describe elements of the acculturative process.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Despite definitions and evidence that acculturation is a two-way process of change, theory and research have dealt mainly with the minorities' adaptations and changes such as immigrants, refugees, and indigenous people in response to their contact with the dominant majority.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Contemporary research has primarily focused on the various strategies of acculturation within societies, the factors influencing the acculturation process and the individuals involved, and the development of interventions aimed at facilitating smoother transitions.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] The history of Western civilization, and in particular the histories of Europe and the United States, are largely defined by patterns of acculturation.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] One of the most notable forms of acculturation is imperialism, the most common progenitor of direct cultural change.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Although these cultural changes may seem simple, the combined results are both robust and complex, impacting both groups and individuals from the original culture and the host culture.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Acculturation with dominance has been researched by sociologists, anthropologists, and historians virtually only, mostly in a colonialism context, due to the dispersal of western European people all over the world over the last five centuries.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] The first psychological theory of acculturation was proposed in W.I.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Thomas and Florian Znaniecki's 1918 study, *The Polish Peasant in Europe and America*.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Long before efforts toward racial and cultural integration in the United States arose, the common process was assimilation.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] In 1964, Milton Gordon's book *Assimilation in American Life* outlined seven stages of the assimilative process, setting the stage for literature on this topic.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Later, Young Yun Kim authored a reiteration of Gordon's work, but argued cross-cultural adaptation as a multi-staged process.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Kim's theory focused on the unitary nature of psychological and social processes and the reciprocal functional personal environment interdependence.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Although this view was the earliest to fuse micro-psychological and macro-social factors into an integrated theory, it was clearly focused on assimilation rather than racial or ethnic integration.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] In opposition to Gudykunst and Kim's adaptive development, Eric M.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Kramer developed his Cultural Fusion theory (2011, 2010, 2000a, 1997a, 2000a, 2011, 2012) maintaining clear, conceptual distinctions between assimilation, adaptation, and integration.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] According to Kramer, assimilation involves conformity to a pre-existing form.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] That is, in Kramer's view, one does not need to unlearn a language to learn another language, or unlearn who he or she is to learn new patterns of dancing, cooking, speaking, etc.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Kramer disagrees with Gudykunst and Kim (2003) in saying that this commingling of language and culture generates cognitive complexity, or being able to switch between cultural repertoires.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] In short, Kramer says that learning is expansion, not unlearning.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Although different acculturation models can be differentiated, the most complete models take into account change occurring in both groups as well as among the members of these interacting groups.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] To understand acculturation at the group level, one must first look at the nature of both cultures before coming into contact with one another.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] A useful approach is Eric Kramer's theory of Dimensional Accrual and Dissociation (DAD).
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Two fundamental premises in Kramer's DAD theory are the concepts of hermeneutics and semiotics, which infer that identity, meaning, communication, and learning all depend on differences or variance.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] According to this view, total assimilation would result in a monoculture void of personal identity, meaning, and communication.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Kramer's DAD theory also utilizes concepts from several scholars, most notably Jean Gebser and Lewis Mumford, to synthesize explanations of widely observed cultural expressions and differences.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Kramer's theory identifies three communication styles (*idolic*, *symbolic*, or *signalic*) in order to explain cultural differences.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] In this theory, there is no single means of communication automatically better, and no last word on intercultural conflict presented.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Kramer presents three connected theories instead: the theory Dimensional Accrual and Dissociation, the Cultural Fusion Theory and the Cultural Churning Theory.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] For instance, according to Kramer's DAD theory, a statue of a god in an *idolic* community is god, and stealing it is a highly punishable offense.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] For example, many people in India believe that statues of the god Ganesh – to take such a statue/god from its temple is more than theft, it is blasphemy.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] *Idolic* reality involves strong emotional identification, where a holy relic does not simply symbolize the sacred, *it is* sacred.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] By contrast, a Christian crucifix follows a *symbolic* nature, where it represents a symbol of God.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Lastly, the *signalic* modality is far less emotional and increasingly dissociated.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Kramer refers to changes in each culture due to acculturation as *co-evolution*.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Kramer also addresses what he calls the *qualities of out vectors* which address the nature in which the former and new cultures make contact.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Kramer uses the phrase "interaction potential" to refer to differences in individual or group acculturative processes.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] For instance, the process of acculturation varies significantly in the case of individuals who were immigrating to the host nation as refugees or immigrants.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Furthermore, this process encompasses the importance of how hospitable the host society is to the newcomer, how welcoming the host is toward accommodating and acquainting the newcomer, and how their interaction affects the host and the newcomer.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] The fourfold model is a bilinear model that categorizes acculturation strategies along two dimensions.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] The first dimension concerns the retention or rejection of an individual's minority or native culture (i.e.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] "Is it considered to be of value to maintain one's identity and characteristics?"), whereas the second dimension concerns the adoption or rejection of the dominant group or host culture.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] ("Is it considered to be of value to maintain relationships with the larger society?") From this, four acculturation strategies emerge.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Studies suggest that individuals' respective acculturation strategy can differ between their private and public life spheres.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] For instance, an individual may reject the values and norms of the dominant culture in their private life (separation), whereas they might adapt to the dominant culture in public parts of their life (i.e., integration or assimilation).
[src:anthropology/acculturation] The fourfold models used to describe individual attitudes of immigrants parallel models used to describe group expectations of the larger society and how groups should acculturate.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] In a melting pot society, in which a harmonious and homogenous culture is promoted, assimilation is the endorsed acculturation strategy.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] In segregationist societies, in which humans are separated into racial, ethnic and/or religious groups in daily life, a separation acculturation strategy is endorsed.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] In a multiculturalist society, in which multiple cultures are accepted and appreciated, individuals are encouraged to adopt an integrationist approach to acculturation.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] In societies where cultural exclusion is promoted, individuals often adopt marginalization strategies of acculturation.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Attitudes towards acculturation, and thus the range of acculturation strategies available, have not been consistent over time.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] For example, for most of American history, policies and attitudes have been based around established ethnic hierarchies with an expectation of one-way assimilation for predominantly White European immigrants.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Although the notion of cultural pluralism has existed since the early 20th century, the recognition and promotion of multiculturalism did not become prominent in America until the 1980s.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Separatism can still be seen today in autonomous religious communities such as the Amish and the Hutterites.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Direct environment also affects the availability, advantage, and choice of various acculturation strategies.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Since immigrants settle in unequal segments of society, immigrants to lower-ranked economic and ethnic hierarchies may face restricted social mobility and membership in a disadvantaged group.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] It is accounted for by the Segmented Assimilation theory, under which the case when immigrant groups or individuals assimilate into the society of the host nation to its various segments' culture.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] One's entry into the upper class, middle class, or lower class is also highly dependent on the socioeconomic status of the last generation.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] On a broad scale study, involving immigrants in 13 immigration-receiving countries, the experience of discrimination was positively related to the maintenance of the immigrants' ethnic culture.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] That is, immigrant communities that retain their culture values and practices are more likely to be discriminated against compared to those that make sacrifices in their culture.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Additional research has also shown that the acculturation process and strategy of immigrants can largely be determined by how accepting of acculturation preference among the host society members is.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] The degree of intergroup and interethnic contact has also been shown to influence acculturation preferences between groups, support for multilingual and multicultural maintenance of minority groups, and openness towards multiculturalism.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Greater comprehension towards out-groups, empathy, building community, lessening prejudice and social distance, and changing good intentions and action assist in the creation of improved interethnic and intercultural relations through intergroup contact.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] There is variation in preferred and ideal acculturation approaches among most people in different aspects of their lives.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] For instance, among immigrants, it is easier and preferable to acculturate towards the host nation's views of politics and government, as compared to acculturation of new beliefs in terms of religion, principles, values, and tradition.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] While acculturation has historically been conceptualized as the result of direct, face-to-face intercultural contact, the proliferation of digital technology has introduced a new dimension to the process.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Researchers have proposed the concept of *digitally mediated acculturation* to describe how digital technologies—such as the internet, social media, and mobile phones—impact the experiences and outcomes of acculturation.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] This perspective does not replace traditional models but suggests that digital acculturation runs concurrently with offline, proximal acculturation.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Cyberspace is treated as a legitimate social space where individuals form identities, negotiate belonging, and interact with both home and host cultures simultaneously.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] This framework suggests that modern acculturation involves navigating new digital stressors as well as new avenues for culture learning and social support.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] It allows migrants to be "virtually present" in a host society before they arrive and to remain "virtually present" in their home society long after they have departed.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Population migration on a large scale all over the world has driven acculturation studies, and how it is impacting health through altering stress, health care utilization, and definitions of health.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] The effects of acculturation on physical health is thought to be a major factor in the immigrant paradox, which argues that first generation immigrants tend to have better health outcomes than non-immigrants.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Even though this phrase has been popularized, most academic literature contends otherwise, or that the immigrants are in better health than the host culture counterparts.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] One prominent explanation for the negative health behaviors and outcomes (e.g. substance use, low birth weight) associated with the acculturation process is the *acculturative stress theory*.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Acculturative stress refers to the stress response of immigrants in response to their experiences of acculturation.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Stressors may be but are not restricted to learning stresses of a second language, preserving the native tongue, reconciling oppositional cultural values, and brokering between host vs. native acceptable social behaviors.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Acculturative stress can manifest in many ways, including but not limited to anxiety, depression, substance abuse, and other forms of mental and physical maladaptation.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Stress caused by acculturation has been heavily documented in phenomenological research on the acculturation of a large variety of immigrants.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] This research has shown that acculturation is a "fatiguing experience requiring a constant stream of bodily energy," and is both an "individual and familial endeavor" involving " consisting of "enduring loneliness caused by seemingly insurmountable language barriers.".
[src:anthropology/acculturation] One of the disparities with respect to risk for acculturative stress is degree of willingness, or migration status, and it can be greatly different if one immigrates into a country as a voluntary immigrant, refugee, asylum seeker, or sojourner.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] According to several studies, voluntary migrants experience roughly 50% less acculturative stress than refugees, making this an important distinction.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] *Refugees:* those who have been involuntarily displaced by persecution, war, or natural disasters.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] *Asylum seekers:* those who willingly leave their native country to flee persecution or violence.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] *Sojourners:* those who relocate to a new country on a time-limited basis and for a specific purpose.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] This group fully intends to return to their native country.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] This form of entry differentiation is significant, yet acculturative stress also varies extensively within and between ethnic groups.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] A great deal of previous academic work has been undertaken with Asian and Latino/a immigrants, but more needs to be done regarding the influence of acculturative stress on other ethnic immigrant groups.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Latinos, higher levels of adoption of the American host culture has been associated with negative effects on health behaviors and outcomes, such as increased risk for depression and discrimination, and increased risk for low self-esteem.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Other studies have found greater levels of acculturation are associated with greater sleep problems.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] However, others also say "experiencing relief and protection in relationships" and "feeling worse and then feeling better about oneself with higher competencies" in the process of acculturation.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Again, these variations may be relate to the age of the immigrant, the manner in which a migrant has departed from his or her home country, and the manner in which a migrant is accepted by source and destination cultures.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] In Belgium, when minority adolescents experienced discrimination, their adoption of the majority culture proespectively predicted less school adaptation and functioning.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Recent research has compared the acculturative processes of documented Mexican-American immigrants and undocumented Mexican-American immigrants and found significant differences in their experiences and levels of acculturative stress.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] These studies highlight the complexities of acculturative stress, the degree of variability in health outcomes, and the need for specificity over generalizations when discussing potential or actual health outcomes.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Researchers have only recently discovered that there is an additional level of complexity in this field, in the form that survey data have grouped different ethnic groups together or have misidentified an ethnic group.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] In generalization, there can be the loss or blurring of subtlety and nuance in terms of the acculturation experience or acculturative stress of an individual or group.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] For example, much of the scholarly literature on this topic uses U.S. census data.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] The Census incorrectly labels Arab-Americans as Caucasian or "White".
[src:anthropology/acculturation] By doing so, this data set omits many factors about the Muslim Arab-American migrant experience, including but not limited to acculturation and acculturative stress.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] This is of particular importance after the events of September 11, 2001, since Muslim Arab-Americans have faced increased prejudice and discrimination, leaving this religious ethnic community with an increased risk of acculturative stress.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Research focusing on the adolescent Muslim Arab American experience of acculturation has also found that youth who experience acculturative stress during the identity formation process are at a higher risk for low self-esteem, anxiety, and depression.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Some researchers argue that education, social support, hopefulness about employment opportunities, financial resources, family cohesion, maintenance of traditional cultural values, and high socioeconomic status (SES) serve as protections or mediators against acculturative stress.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Previous work shows that limited education, low SES, and underemployment all increase acculturative stress.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] When individuals of a specific culture find themselves in contact with another culture (host) which is mainly more set up in the region where they live, elements of the host culture will most likely be appropriated and blended with elements of the people's native culture.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] In cases of extended contact, cultures have shared and mixed food, music, dances, attire, implements, and technologies.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] This type of cultural exchange is attributed to selective acculturation, which is the act of preserving cultural content by learning about the way those individuals use language, religious belief, and family norms.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Cultural exchange can either occur naturally through extended contact, or more quickly though cultural appropriation or cultural imperialism.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Cultural appropriation is the process of adopting specific elements of one culture by members a different cultural group.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] It can include the introduction of forms of dress or personal adornment, music and art, religion, language, or behavior.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] These elements are typically imported into the existing culture, and may have wildly different meanings or lack the subtleties of their original cultural context.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Because of this, cultural appropriation for financial gain is oftentimes condemned, and has sometimes been termed "cultural theft".
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Cultural imperialism is the practice of promoting the culture or language of one nation in another, usually occurring in situations in which assimilation is the dominant strategy of acculturation.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Cultural imperialism can take the form of an active, formal policy or a general attitude regarding cultural superiority.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] In some instances, acculturation results in the adoption of another country's language, which is then modified over time to become a new, distinct, language.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] For example, Hanzi, the written language of Chinese language, has been adapted and modified by other nearby cultures, including: Japan (as kanji), Korea (as hanja), and Vietnam (as chữ Hán).
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Jews, often living as ethnic minorities, developed distinct languages derived from the common languages of the countries in which they lived (for example, Yiddish from High German and Ladino from Old Spanish).
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Another common effect of acculturation on language is the formation of pidgin languages.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Pidgin is a mixed language that has developed to help communication between members of different cultures in contact, usually occurring in situations of trade or colonialism.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] For example, Pidgin English is a simplified form of English mixed with some of the language of another culture.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Some pidgin languages can develop into creole languages, which are spoken as a first language.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Language plays a pivotal role in cultural heritage, serving as both a foundation for group identity and a means for transmitting culture in situations of contact between languages.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Language acculturation strategies, attitudes and identities can also influence the sociolinguistic development of languages in bi/multilingual contexts.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Acculturation impacts eating habits and intake at various levels.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Studies have confirmed that dietary habits are precarious and consumed in secret, and change is a slow process.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Learning to eat new food relies on the accessibility of indigenous ingredients, preparation simplicity, and price; thus, an immediate adjustment is expected to take place.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Food acculturation aspects include food preparation, presentation, and consumption.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Various societies prepare, present, and consume food differently.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] If one is exposed to another society for a long time, one is likely to learn aspects of the "host" society's food culture and apply them to oneself.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] In situations like these, acculturation is greatly dependent on general food information, or the information regarding the particular foods various cultures generally consume, the media, and social interaction.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] It makes various cultures interact with each other, and as a result, some of their elements blend and also become more acceptable to the people of each of the involved cultures.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Anthropologists have made a semantic distinction between group and individual levels of acculturation.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] In such instances, the term *transculturation* is used to define individual foreign-origin acculturation, and occurs on a smaller scale with less visible impact.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Scholars making this distinction use the term "acculturation" only to address large-scale cultural transactions.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Acculturation, then, is the process by which migrants gain new information and insight about the norms and values of their culture and adapt their behaviors to the host culture.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Research long assumed that the integrationist model of acculturation leads to the most favorable psychological outcomes and marginalization to the least favorable, despite some early criticism.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Although a correlational meta-analysis of the acculturation literature and a large-scale study led by John W.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Berry (2006) found that integration correlated with better psychological and sociocultural adaptation, recent longitudinal meta-analyses find no support for a meaningful causal relationship.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Critically, given the high heterogeneity in effect, the association between integration and adaptation can be expected to be negative almost 30% of the time.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Several theorists have stated that the fourfold models of acculturation are too simplistic to have predictive validity.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Some common criticisms of such models include the fact that individuals don't often fall neatly into any of the four categories, and that there is very little evidence for the applied existence of the marginalization acculturation strategy.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] In addition, the bi-directionality of acculturation means that whenever two groups are engaged in cultural exchange, there are 16 permutations of acculturation strategies possible (e.g. an integrationist individual within an assimilationist host culture).
[src:anthropology/acculturation] According to the research, another critique of the fourfold model of acculturation is that the people are less likely to cultivate a self-perception but either not assimilate other cultures or continuing the heritage cultures.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Acculturation, which focuses on the processes of cultural change, is inherently concerned with causal relationships.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] However, a significant limitation of the field is that nearly all existing research has been correlational in nature, making it impossible to infer causality.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Therefore, major notions such as the integration hypothesis studied in hundreds of studies still lack solid empirical support.
[src:anthropology/acculturation] Calls have been made to address this issue by considering acculturation from a developmental, longitudinal perspective.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Status is important sociologically because it comes with achieved rights, obligations, behaviors, and duties that people occupying a certain position are expected or encouraged to perform.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Those expectations are referred to as roles.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] For instance, the role of a professor includes teaching students, answering questions, and being impartial and appropriate.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Ascribed status is a position assigned to individuals or groups based on traits beyond their control, such as sex, race, or parental social status.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] It is usually associated with closed societies.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Achieved status is distinguished from ascribed status by virtue of being earned through the set of accomplished tasks and/or goals.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Many positions are a mixture of achievement and ascription.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] For instance, a person who has achieved the status of being a physician is more likely to have the ascribed status of being born into a wealthy family.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] That is usually associated with open societies or social-class societies.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Social mobility refers to one's ability to move their status either up or down the social stratification system, compared with their family's status in early life.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Some people with achieved status have improved their position in the social system by their own merit and achievements.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] However others may have either cheated or unintentionally gained status.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Someone may also have achieved status that decreases their position within the social system, such as by becoming a notorious criminal.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] A society in which people's position in that society can change by their actions, by increasing or decreasing, can be referred to as an open system.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] A closed system society allows less social mobility.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Cultural capital is a concept, developed by the sociologist Pierre Bourdieu.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] It can refer to both achieved and ascribed characteristics, which are desirable qualities (either material or symbolic) that contribute to one's social status: any advantages that a person has and give him or her a higher status in society.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] It may include high expectations, forms of knowledge, skill, or education.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Parents provide children with cultural capital, the attitudes and knowledge that make the educational system a comfortable familiar place in which they can succeed easily.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] There are other types of capital as well.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Social capital refers to one's membership in groups, relationships, and networks.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] It can also have a significant impact on achievement level.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Industrialization has led to a vast increase in the possible standard of living for the average person but also made that increase necessary.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] For the productivity of the average worker to rise, he or she had to receive far more education and training, which successively made the average worker much less replaceable and thus more powerful.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Hence, it became necessary to satisfy workers' demands for a larger share.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] According to the sociologist Rodney Stark, few Americans believe that coming from a wealthy family or having political connections is necessary to get ahead.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] In contrast, many people in other industrialized nations think those factors are necessary for advancement.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Americans are more likely than the people in those nations to rate "hard work" as very important for getting ahead.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Most nations value hard work, but Italians, for example, are hardly more likely to rate it as very important than they are to think that political connections are needed.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] People with a lower income will generally be a better example of moving up in the social stratification and achieving status.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] That holds to be evident in most cases because those who accrue a lower income may either have the motivation to achieve a greater status, or face financial pressure, and attempt to follow their own ambitions and hard work.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Those of higher income may the result of achieving status, however other factors are at play, such as scarcity of skills, promotion abilities.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Positions may also pay better in some areas than others.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] In other cases, the people with higher incomes may have unjustly acquired that position or were ascribed their status and income (such as monarchs, family-run businesses, etc.).
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] They may have also gained a higher income position by chance.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Those without the privilege of ascribing their status generally have the greater motivation of achieving their own status.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] The general economic well-being of the society in which they live also tends to be another factor in their status and the extent that they are able to achieve their status.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] For example, Americans are less likely than people in other industrialized nations to object to current income variances.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] According to Rodney Stark, in 1992, only 27% of Americans strongly agreed that income disparities in their country were too large.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] In contrast, more than half of Russians, Italians, and Bulgarians agreed with that statement.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] In all societies, a person's social status is the result of both ascribed and achieved characteristics.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] One's status in medieval Europe was primarily based on ascription.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] People born into the noble class were likely to keep a high position and people born of peasants were likely to stay in a low position.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] This political system is known as feudalism and does not allow for much social mobility.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Bolivia used to have newspaper advertisements that claimed to have land, animals and peasants for sale.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] The peasants were not necessarily slaves but placed in their social class and required to work because they were bound to the land on which they lived and that they farmed.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] That sort of social interaction is based mainly on the people's strong belief of tradition and to uphold the actions of the past.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] In 1971, Ernesto Laclau addressed the argument of Latin America was feudalist or capitalist.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] He determined that the social system was very different from the capitalist system in Europe and the United States and so Latin America would be more closely related to having a feudalist approach to social interaction.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] The formation of a hierarchy differs from the polarities of both given and achieved status.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] In caste systems, ascription is the overpowering basis for status.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Traditional society in South Asia and other parts of the world such as Egypt, India, Bali, Tibet, and Japan were composed of castes.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Each group was limited to certain occupations.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Low-paying occupations such as collecting garbage were reserved for one caste, whose members were excluded from holding any other occupation.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] Correspondingly, highly skilled occupations, such as being a priest or a goldsmith, were reserved for another caste.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] However, some people managed through talent and luck to rise above their given caste.
[src:anthropology/achieved-status] For example, great aptitude as a soldier was often a way to reach a higher status.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] The association has grown into a network that connects more than 7,000 anthropologists from Spain, Portugal, and the Latin-American countries.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] In November 2002, the association was legally constituted and recognized by the Minister of the Interior of Spain.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] Since 2001, AIBR has published the scientific journal *AIBR.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] Revista de Antropología Iberoamericana* ('Journal of Iberoamerican Anthropology') every four months, both electronically and on paper.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] In July 2015, the association held its first international conference under the global theme "The human being: cultures, origins, and destiny", with over 800 delegates gathering in Madrid, Spain.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] The meeting was presented by anthropologist Didier Fassin of the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, and closed with a lecture by Aurora González Echevarria of the Autonomous University of Barcelona.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] The Second AIBR International Conference took place in Barcelona in September 2016, under the global theme "Identity: Bridges, Thresholds, and Barriers".
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] This edition opened with a plenary address by Arturo Escobar (University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill), and continued with lectures by Tim Ingold (University of Aberdeen), Verena Stolcke (Autonomous University of Barcelona), and Manuel Delgado (University of Barcelona).
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] The Third AIBR International Conference took place in Puerto Vallarta, Mexico, in November 2017 and was the first edition of the AIBR Conference to take place in the Americas.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] The theme was "Travels, crossings, displacements", and the conference began with an inaugural lecture by Marc Augé of the École des Hautes Études en Sciences Sociales (EHESS).
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] The Fourth AIBR International Conference of Anthropology took place in Granada, Spain, under the general theme "Dialogues, Encounters, and Stories from the Souths".
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] This edition began with a plenary session by Nigel Barley and closed with a plenary session by Paul Stoller (West Chester University, Pennsylvania).
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] Additionally, a new form of meeting was introduced, with the first "Diálogo a Dos" between María Teresa del Valle (University of Basque Country) and Mónica Tarducci (University of Buenos Aires) on the connections between anthropology and feminism.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] List of plenary speakers who have participated in both the opening and closing sessions and who have been recognized for contributions to the discipline in the international arena.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] Since 2013, the AIBR Best Article Award in Iberoamerican Anthropology has been awarded annually to the best article from the previous calendar year.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] This award is sponsored by the AIBR journal and comes with a prize of EUR 450.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] The winning article and articles shortlisted for the Award are published in the scientific journal AIBR.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] AIBR is not affiliated with any university or academic institution, nor does it follow any political or religious faith.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] It is a private, independent initiative that anyone may join.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] It is funded by projects and activities, and the annual subscription fees provided by its members.
[src:anthropology/aibr-asociación-de-antropólogos-iberoamericanos-en-red] AIBR has belonged to the International Union of Anthropological and Ethnological Sciences (IUAES) since July 2005.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Archaeology, often referred to as the "anthropology of the past," explores human activity by examining physical remains.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] In North America and Asia, it is generally regarded as a branch of anthropology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] In contrast, in Europe, it is considered either an independent discipline or a subfield of related disciplines such as history and palaeontology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The abstract noun *anthropology* is first attested in reference to history.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Its present use first appeared in Renaissance Germany in the works of Magnus Hundt and Otto Casmann.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Their Neo-Latin **anthropologia** derived from the combining forms of the Greek words *ánthrōpos* (ἄνθρωπος, "human") and *lógos* (λόγος, "study").
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Its adjectival form appeared in the works of Aristotle.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It began to be used in English, possibly via French **Anthropologie**, by the early 18th century.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Various short-lived organizations of anthropologists had already been formed.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The Société Ethnologique de Paris, the first to use the term *ethnology*, was founded in 1839 and focused on the methodical study of human races.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] After the death of its founder, William Frédéric Edwards, in 1842, it gradually declined in activity until it eventually dissolved in 1862.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Meanwhile, the Ethnological Society of New York, now the American Ethnological Society, was founded on its model in 1842, as well as the Ethnological Society of London in 1843, a break-away group of the Aborigines' Protection Society.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Anthropology and many other current fields are the intellectual results of the comparative methods developed in the early 19th century.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Theorists in diverse fields such as anatomy, linguistics, and ethnology started making feature-by-feature comparisons of their subject matters and were beginning to suspect that similarities between animals, languages, and folkways were the result of processes or laws unknown to them then.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] For them, the publication of Charles Darwin's *On the Origin of Species* was the epiphany of everything they had begun to suspect.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Darwin himself arrived at his conclusions through comparison of species he had seen in agronomy and in the wild.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Darwin and Wallace unveiled the theory of evolution in the late 1850s.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] There was an immediate rush to bring it into the social sciences.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Paul Broca in Paris was in the process of breaking away from the Société de biologie to form the first of the explicitly anthropological societies, the Société d'Anthropologie de Paris, meeting for the first time in Paris in 1859.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] When he read Darwin, he became an immediate convert to *Transformisme*, as the French called evolutionism.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] His definition now became "the study of the human group, considered as a whole, in its details, and in relation to the rest of nature".
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Broca discovered the speech center of the human brain, today called Broca's area.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] His interest was mainly in biological anthropology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Still, a German philosopher specializing in psychology, Theodor Waitz, took up the theme of general and social anthropology in his six-volume work, entitled *Die Anthropologie der Naturvölker*, 1859–1864.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The title was soon translated as "The Anthropology of Primitive Peoples".
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The last two volumes were published posthumously.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Waitz defined anthropology as "the science of the nature of man".
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Following Broca's lead, Waitz points out that anthropology is a new field that would gather material from other fields but would differ from them in its use of comparative anatomy, physiology, and psychology to differentiate man from "the animals nearest to him".
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] He stresses that the data of comparison must be empirical, gathered by experimentation.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The history of civilization, as well as ethnology, is to be brought into the comparison.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It is to be presumed fundamentally that the species, man, is a unity, and that "the same laws of thought are applicable to all men".
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Waitz was influential among British ethnologists.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] In 1863, the explorer Richard Francis Burton and the speech therapist James Hunt broke away from the Ethnological Society of London to form the Anthropological Society of London, which henceforward would follow the path of the new anthropology rather than just ethnology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It was the 2nd society dedicated to general anthropology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Representatives from the French *Société* were present, though not Broca.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] In his keynote address, printed in the first volume of its new publication, *The Anthropological Review*, Hunt stressed the work of Waitz, adopting his definitions as a standard.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Among the first associates were the young Edward Burnett Tylor, inventor of cultural anthropology, and his brother Alfred Tylor, a geologist.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Previously Edward had referred to himself as an ethnologist; subsequently, an anthropologist.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Similar organizations in other countries followed: the Anthropological Society of Madrid (1865), the American Anthropological Association (1902), the Anthropological Society of Vienna (1870), the Italian Society of Anthropology and Ethnology (1871), and many others.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The majority of these were evolutionists.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] One notable exception was the Berlin Society for Anthropology, Ethnology, and Prehistory (1869), founded by Rudolph Virchow, known for his vituperative attacks on the evolutionists.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Not religious himself, he insisted that Darwin's conclusions lacked empirical foundation.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] During the last three decades of the 19th century, a proliferation of anthropological societies and associations occurred, most independent, most publishing their own journals, and all international in membership and association.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The major theorists belonged to these organizations.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] They supported the gradual osmosis of anthropology curricula into the major institutions of higher learning.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] By 1898, 48 educational institutions in 13 countries offered some anthropology courses.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] None of the 75 faculty members were under a department named anthropology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Some consider anthropology to have become a tool for colonisers, who study their subjects to gain a better understanding and control.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Anthropology, as a specialized field of academic study, developed significantly by the end of the 19th century.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Beginning in the early 20th century, the field saw rapid expansion, to the point where many of the world's higher education institutions typically included anthropology departments.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Thousands of anthropology departments have come into existence, and the field has diversified from a few major subdivisions to dozens more.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Practical anthropology, the use of anthropological knowledge and techniques to solve specific problems, has arrived; for example, the presence of buried victims might prompt the use of a forensic archaeologist to reconstruct the final scene.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The field has seen rapid growth on a global scale as well; the International Union of Anthropological and Ethnological Sciences contains members from over 50 countries.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Cultural anthropology, in particular, has emphasized cultural relativism, holism, and the use of findings to frame cultural critiques.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] This has been particularly prominent in the United States, from Boas' arguments against 19th-century racial ideology, through Margaret Mead's advocacy for gender equality and sexual liberation, to current criticisms of post-colonial oppression and promotion of multiculturalism.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Ethnography is one of its primary research designs as well as the text that is generated from anthropological fieldwork.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] In Great Britain and the Commonwealth countries, the British tradition of social anthropology tends to dominate.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] In the United States, anthropology has traditionally been divided into the four field approach developed by Franz Boas in the early 20th century: *biological* or *physical* anthropology; *social*, *cultural*, or *sociocultural* anthropology; archaeological anthropology; and linguistic anthropology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] These fields frequently overlap but tend to use different methodologies and techniques.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] European countries with overseas colonies tended to practice more ethnology (a term coined and defined by Adam F.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It is sometimes referred to as sociocultural anthropology in parts of the world influenced by the European tradition.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Anthropology is a global discipline involving the humanities, social sciences, and natural sciences.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Early anthropology originated in Classical Greece and Persia and studied and tried to understand observable cultural diversity.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] As such, anthropology has been central in the development of several new (late 20th century) interdisciplinary fields such as cognitive science, global studies, and various ethnic studies.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Sociocultural anthropology has been heavily influenced by structuralist and postmodern theories, as well as a shift toward the analysis of modern societies.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] During the 1970s and 1990s, there was an epistemological shift away from the positivist traditions that had largely informed the discipline.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] During this shift, enduring questions about the nature and production of knowledge came to occupy a central place in cultural and social anthropology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] In contrast, archaeology and biological anthropology remained largely positivist.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Sociocultural anthropology draws together the principal axes of cultural anthropology and social anthropology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Cultural anthropology is the comparative study of the manifold ways in which people *make sense* of the world around them.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] In contrast, social anthropology is the study of the *relationships* among individuals and groups.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] In that, it helps develop an understanding of social structures, typically of others and other populations (such as minorities, subgroups, dissidents, etc.).
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] There is no hard-and-fast distinction between them, and these categories overlap to a considerable degree.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Inquiry in sociocultural anthropology is guided in part by cultural relativism, the attempt to understand other societies in terms of their own cultural symbols and values.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Accepting other cultures in their own terms moderates reductionism in cross-cultural comparison.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] This project is often accommodated in the field of ethnography.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Ethnography can refer to both a methodology and the product of ethnographic research, i.e., an ethnographic monograph.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] As a methodology, ethnography is based upon long-term fieldwork within a community or other research site.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Participant observation is one of the foundational methods of social and cultural anthropology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Ethnology involves the systematic comparison of different cultures.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The process of participant observation can be especially helpful for understanding a culture from an emic (conceptual, vs. etic, or technical) point of view.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The study of kinship and social organization is a central focus of sociocultural anthropology, as kinship is a human universal.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Comparison across cultures is a key methodological element in sociocultural anthropology, including the industrialized (and de-industrialized) West.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The Standard Cross-Cultural Sample (SCCS) includes 186 such cultures.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Biological anthropology and physical anthropology are synonymous terms to describe anthropological research focused on the study of humans and other primates in their biological, evolutionary, and demographic dimensions.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It examines the biological and social factors that have affected the evolution of humans and other primates, and that generate, maintain or change contemporary genetic and physiological variation.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Subfields include forensic anthropology, paleoanthropology, dental anthropology, primatology, and human biology, among others.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Nineteenth- and twentieth-century America and Europe were formative periods for many scientific disciplines, and racism played a significant role in motivating certain avenues of research, including the early development of bioarchaeology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] This racist foundation shaped attitudes for decades, reinforcing the belief among many anthropologists that they held inherent authority over the human remains and burial sites they encountered.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Recognizing this history is crucial, as its effects persist today in the form of damaged evidence, ethical challenges, and harmful professional assumptions.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Archaeology is the study of the human past through its material remains.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Artifacts, faunal remains, and human-altered landscapes are evidence of the cultural and material lives of past societies.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Archaeologists examine material remains to deduce patterns of past human behavior and cultural practices.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Ethnoarchaeology is a branch of archaeology that studies the practices and material remains of living human groups to understand better the evidence left behind by past human groups presumed to have lived in similar ways.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Linguistic anthropology (not to be confused with anthropological linguistics) seeks to understand the processes of human communications, verbal and non-verbal, variation in language across time and space, the social uses of language, and the relationship between language and culture.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It is the branch of anthropology that brings linguistic methods to bear on anthropological problems, linking the analysis of linguistic forms and processes to the interpretation of sociocultural processes.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Linguistic anthropologists often draw on related fields including sociolinguistics, pragmatics, cognitive linguistics, semiotics, discourse analysis, and narrative analysis.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Ethnography is a method of analysing social or cultural interaction.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It often involves participant observation, though an ethnographer may also draw from texts written by participants in social interactions.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Ethnography views first-hand experience and social context as important.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Tim Ingold distinguishes ethnography from anthropology, arguing that anthropology seeks to construct general theories of human experience applicable to novel settings, while ethnography concerns itself with fidelity.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] He argues that the anthropologist must make his writing consistent with their understanding of literature and other theory but notes that ethnography may be of use to the anthropologists and the fields inform one another.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] One of the central problems in the anthropology of art concerns the universality of 'art' as a cultural phenomenon.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Several anthropologists have noted that the Western categories of 'painting', 'sculpture', or 'literature', conceived as independent artistic activities, do not exist, or exist in a significantly different form, in most non-Western contexts.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] To solve this, anthropologists of art have focused on formal features in objects which, without exclusively being 'artistic', have certain evident 'aesthetic' qualities.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Boas' *Primitive Art*, Claude Lévi-Strauss' *The Way of the Masks* (1982) or Geertz's 'Art as Cultural System' (1983) are examples in this trend of transforming the anthropology of 'art' into an anthropology of culturally specific 'aesthetics'.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Media anthropology emphasizes ethnographic studies as a means of understanding producers, audiences, and other cultural and social aspects of mass media.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The types of ethnographic contexts explored range from media production (e.g., ethnographies of newspaper newsrooms, journalists in the field, and film production) to media reception, following audiences in their everyday responses to media.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Other types include cyber anthropology, a relatively new area of internet research, as well as ethnographies of other areas of research that involve media, such as development work, social movements, or health education.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] This is in addition to many classic ethnographic contexts, where media such as radio, the press, new media, and television have started to make their presences felt since the early 1990s.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Ethnomusicology is an academic field encompassing various approaches to the study of music (broadly defined) that emphasize its cultural, social, material, cognitive, biological, and other dimensions or contexts, rather than its isolated sound component or any particular repertoire.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Ethnomusicology can be applied across a wide range of fields, including teaching, politics, and cultural anthropology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] While the origins of ethnomusicology date back to the 18th and 19th centuries, it was formally termed "ethnomusicology" by Dutch scholar Jaap Kunst c.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Later, the influence of study in this area spawned the creation of the periodical *Ethnomusicology* and the Society of Ethnomusicology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Visual anthropology is concerned, in part, with the study and production of ethnographic photography, film, and, since the mid-1990s, new media.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] While the term is sometimes used interchangeably with ethnographic film, visual anthropology also encompasses the anthropological study of visual representation, including areas such as performance, museums, art, and the production and reception of mass media.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Visual representations from all cultures, such as sandpaintings, tattoos, sculptures and reliefs, cave paintings, scrimshaw, jewelry, hieroglyphs, paintings, and photographs are included in the focus of visual anthropology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Economic anthropology seeks to explain human economic behavior across the widest historical, geographic, and cultural scope.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It has a complex relationship with the discipline of economics, which it is highly critical of.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Its origins as a sub-field of anthropology begin with the Polish-British founder of anthropology, Bronisław Malinowski, and his French compatriot, Marcel Mauss, on the nature of gift-giving exchange (or reciprocity) as an alternative to market exchange.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Economic anthropology remains, for the most part, focused upon exchange.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The school of thought derived from Marx and known as political economy focuses on production, in contrast.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Economic anthropologists have abandoned the primitivist niche they were relegated to by economists, and have now turned to examine corporations, banks, and the global financial system from an anthropological perspective.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Political economy in anthropology is the application of the theories and methods of historical materialism to the traditional concerns of anthropology, including, but not limited to, non-capitalist societies.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Political economy introduced questions of history and colonialism to ahistorical anthropological theories of social structure and culture.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Three main areas of interest rapidly developed.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The first of these areas concerned the "pre-capitalist" societies subject to evolutionary "tribal" stereotypes.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Sahlin's work on hunter-gatherers as the "original affluent society" did much to dissipate that image.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The second area was concerned with the vast majority of the world's population at the time, the peasantry, many of whom were involved in complex revolutionary wars, such as in Vietnam.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The third area was on colonialism, imperialism, and the creation of the capitalist world-system.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] More recently, these political economists have more directly addressed issues of industrial (and post-industrial) capitalism around the world.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Applied anthropology refers to the application of the method and theory of anthropology to the analysis and solution of practical problems.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It is a "complex of related, research-based, instrumental methods which produce change or stability in specific cultural systems through the provision of data, initiation of direct action, and/or the formulation of policy".
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Applied anthropology is the practical side of anthropological research; it includes researcher involvement and activism within the participating community.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It is closely related to development anthropology (distinct from the more critical anthropology of development).
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Anthropology of development tends to view development from a *critical* perspective.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The issues addressed, and the implications for the approach, involve pondering why, if a key development goal is to alleviate poverty, poverty is increasing.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Why is there such a gap between plans and outcomes?
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Why are those working in development so willing to disregard history and the lessons it might offer?
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Why is development so externally driven rather than having an internal basis?
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] In short, why does so much planned development fail?
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Feminist anthropology is a four-field approach to anthropology (archeological, biological, cultural, linguistic) that seeks to reduce male bias in research findings, anthropological hiring practices, and the scholarly production of knowledge.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Anthropology often engages with feminists from non-Western traditions, whose perspectives and experiences can differ from those of white feminists of Europe, America, and elsewhere.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] From the perspective of the Western world, such 'peripheral' perspectives have historically been ignored, viewed only from an outsider's perspective, and regarded as less valid or less important than knowledge from the Western world.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Exploring and addressing that double bias against women from marginalized racial or ethnic groups is of particular interest in intersectional feminist anthropology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] This correction of systemic bias may include mainstream feminist theory, history, linguistics, archaeology, and anthropology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Feminist anthropologists are often concerned with the construction of gender across societies.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Gender constructs are of particular interest in the study of sexism.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Clair Drake, Vera Mae Green was, until "[w]ell into the 1960s", the only African American female anthropologist who was also a Caribbeanist.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] She studied ethnic and family relations in the Caribbean and the United States, and thereby sought to improve the way black life, experiences, and culture were studied.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] However, Zora Neale Hurston, although often primarily considered to be a literary author, was trained in anthropology by Franz Boas, and published *Tell my Horse* about her "anthropological observations" of voodoo in the Caribbean (1938).
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Feminist anthropology is inclusive of the anthropology of birth as a specialization, which is the anthropological study of pregnancy and childbirth within cultures and societies.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Medical anthropology is an interdisciplinary field that studies "human health and disease, health care systems, and biocultural adaptation".
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It is believed that William Caudell was the first to discover the field of medical anthropology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Currently, research in medical anthropology is one of the main areas of growth in anthropology as a whole.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Other subjects that have become central to medical anthropology worldwide are violence and social suffering (Farmer, 1999, 2003; Beneduce, 2010), as well as other issues that involve physical and psychological harm and suffering that are not a result of illness.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] On the other hand, some fields intersect with medical anthropology in research methodology and theoretical production, such as *cultural psychiatry*, *transcultural psychiatry*, and *ethnopsychiatry*.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Nutritional anthropology is a synthetic concept that examines the interplay among economic systems, nutritional status, and food security, and how changes in the former affect the latter.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] If economic and environmental changes in a community affect access to food, food security, and dietary health, then this interplay between culture and biology is in turn connected to broader historical and economic trends associated with globalization.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Nutritional status affects overall health, work performance potential, and the potential for economic development (whether in terms of human development or traditional Western models) for any given group of people.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Psychological anthropology is an interdisciplinary subfield of anthropology that studies the interaction of cultural and mental processes.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] This subfield tends to focus on ways in which humans' development and enculturation within a particular cultural group – with its own history, language, practices, and conceptual categories – shape processes of human cognition, emotion, perception, motivation, and mental health.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It also examines how the understanding of cognition, emotion, motivation, and similar psychological processes inform or constrain our models of cultural and social processes.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Cognitive anthropology is concerned with what people from different groups know and how that implicit knowledge shapes how they perceive and relate to the world around them.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Transpersonal anthropology studies the relationship between altered states of consciousness and culture.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] As with transpersonal psychology, the field is much concerned with altered states of consciousness (ASC) and transpersonal experience.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] However, the field differs from mainstream transpersonal psychology in taking more cognizance of cross-cultural issues – for instance, the roles of myth, ritual, diet, and text in evoking and interpreting extraordinary experiences.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Political anthropology concerns the structure of political systems, viewed in light of the structure of societies.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The turn towards complex societies meant that political themes were taken up at two main levels.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Firstly, anthropologists continued to study political organization and political phenomena that lay outside the state-regulated sphere (as in patron-client relations or tribal political organization).
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Secondly, anthropologists gradually began to develop a disciplinary concern with states and their institutions (and with the relationship between formal and informal political institutions).
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] An anthropology of the state has developed into a thriving field today.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Geertz's comparative work on "Negara", the Balinese state, is an early, famous example.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Legal anthropology or anthropology of law specializes in "the cross-cultural study of social ordering".
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Earlier legal anthropological research often focused more narrowly on conflict management, crime, sanctions, or formal regulation.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] More recent applications include issues such as human rights, legal pluralism, and political uprisings.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Cyborg anthropology originated as a sub-focus group within the American Anthropological Association's annual meeting in 1993.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The sub-group was very closely related to STS and the Society for the Social Studies of Science.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Donna Haraway's 1985 *Cyborg Manifesto* could be considered the founding document of cyborg anthropology, as it first explores the philosophical and sociological ramifications of the term.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Cyborg anthropology studies humankind and its relations with the technological systems it has built, specifically modern systems that have reflexively shaped notions of what it means to be human.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Digital anthropology is the study of the relationship between humans and digital-era technology and extends to various areas where anthropology and technology intersect.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It is sometimes grouped with sociocultural anthropology, and sometimes considered part of material culture.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The field is new and thus has a variety of names and emphases.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] These include techno-anthropology, digital ethnography, cyberanthropology, and virtual anthropology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Ecological anthropology is defined as the "study of cultural adaptations to environments".
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The sub-field is also defined as, "the study of relationships between a population of humans and their biophysical environment".
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The focus of its research concerns "how cultural beliefs and practices helped human populations adapt to their environments, and how their environments change across space and time.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The contemporary perspective of environmental anthropology, and arguably at least the backdrop, if not the focus of most of the ethnographies and cultural fieldworks of today, is political ecology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Many characterize this new perspective as more informed with culture, politics, and power, globalization, localized issues, century anthropology, and more.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The focus and data interpretation is often used for arguments for/against or creation of policy, and to prevent corporate exploitation and damage of land.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Often, the observer has become an active part of the struggle, either directly (organizing, participating) or indirectly (through articles, documentaries, books, ethnographies).
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Such is the case with environmental justice advocate Melissa Checker and her relationship with the people of Hyde Park.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Social sciences, such as anthropology, can offer interdisciplinary approaches to environmental issues.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Professor Kay Milton, Director of the Anthropology research network in the School of History and Anthropology, describes anthropology as distinctive, with its most distinguishing feature being its interest in non-industrial indigenous and traditional societies.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Anthropological theory is distinct because of the consistent presence of the concept of culture; not an exclusive topic but a central position in the study and a deep concern with the human condition.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Environmental discourse appears to be characterized by a high degree of globalization.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] (The troubling problem is borrowing non-indigenous practices and creating standards, concepts, philosophies, and practices in Western countries.) Anthropology and environmental discourse have now become a distinct position in anthropology as a discipline.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Knowledge about diversities in human culture can be important in addressing environmental problems - anthropology is now a study of human ecology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Human activity is the most important agent in creating environmental change, a finding commonly found in human ecology, and it can claim a central place in how environmental problems are examined and addressed.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Other ways anthropology contributes to environmental discourse include serving as theorists and analysts, or refining definitions to be more neutral/universal, etc.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] In the context of environmentalism, the term typically refers to the concern that the environment should be protected, particularly from the harmful effects of human activities.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Environmentalism itself can be expressed in many ways.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Ethnohistory is the study of ethnographic cultures and indigenous customs through the examination of historical records.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It is also the study of the history of various ethnic groups that may or may not exist today.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Ethnohistory uses both historical and ethnographic data as its foundation.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Its historical methods and materials go beyond the standard use of documents and manuscripts.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Practitioners recognize the utility of such source material as maps, music, paintings, photography, folklore, oral tradition, site exploration, archaeological materials, museum collections, enduring customs, language, and place names.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] The anthropology of religion involves the study of religious institutions in relation to other social institutions, and the comparison of religious beliefs and practices across cultures.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Modern anthropology assumes that there is complete continuity between magical thinking and religion, and that every religion is a cultural product created by the human community that worships it.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Urban anthropology is concerned with issues of urbanization, poverty, and neoliberalism.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Ulf Hannerz quotes a 1960s remark that traditional anthropologists were "a notoriously agoraphobic lot, anti-urban by definition".
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Various social processes in the Western World as well as in the "Third World" (the latter being the habitual focus of attention of anthropologists) brought the attention of "specialists in 'other cultures'" closer to their homes.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] There are two main approaches to urban anthropology: examining the types of cities or examining the social issues within the cities.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] These two methods overlap and depend on each other.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] When defining different types of cities, one would use social, economic, and political factors to categorize them.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] By directly looking at the different social issues, one would also be studying how they affect the dynamic of the city.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Anthrozoology (also known as "human–animal studies") is the study of the interaction between living things.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It is an interdisciplinary field that overlaps with several other disciplines, including anthropology, ethology, medicine, psychology, veterinary medicine, and zoology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] A major focus of anthrozoologic research is the quantification of the positive effects of human-animal relationships on either party and the study of their interactions.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It includes scholars from a diverse range of fields, including anthropology, sociology, biology, and philosophy.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Biocultural anthropology is the scientific exploration of the relationships between human biology and culture.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Physical anthropologists throughout the first half of the 20th century viewed this relationship from a racial perspective; that is, from the assumption that typological human biological differences lead to cultural differences.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] After World War II the emphasis began to shift toward an effort to explore the role culture plays in shaping human biology.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Evolutionary anthropology is the interdisciplinary study of the evolution of human physiology and human behaviour and the relation between hominins and non-hominin primates.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Evolutionary anthropology is based in natural science and social science, combining the human development with socioeconomic factors.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] Evolutionary anthropology is concerned with both the biological and cultural evolution of humans, past and present.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It is based on a scientific approach, and brings together fields such as archaeology, behavioral ecology, psychology, primatology, and genetics.
[src:anthropology/anthropology-p01] It is a dynamic and interdisciplinary field, drawing on many lines of evidence to understand the human experience, past and present.
